## Key Design Decisions

### 1. Zustand over Context for state
The call store uses `useCallStore` (Zustand) instead of React Context state to avoid re-rendering the entire component tree on every state change. Components subscribe to **individual selectors** (e.g., `useCallStore(s => s.isMuted)`) so only the relevant control button re-renders.

### 2. MediaStream as refs, not state
`localStreamRef` and `remoteStreamRef` are `useRef` values — setting a `MediaStream` into React state would trigger re-renders on every frame. Instead, we use `CustomEvent` dispatch to notify the memoized `VideoElement` component when streams change.

### 3. Trickle ICE with buffering
The WebRTC engine buffers ICE candidates received before [setRemoteDescription()](file:///d:/projects/social/frontend/src/features/call/engine/webrtc.engine.ts#251-266) is called, then flushes them automatically. This prevents the common race condition where candidates arrive before the remote SDP.

### 4. Opus SDP preference
The engine rewrites SDP to prefer Opus codec for audio, ensuring the best audio quality and lowest latency path.

### 5. Separated upgrade renegotiation
Video upgrade uses `addTrack()` + new [createOffer()](file:///d:/projects/social/frontend/src/features/call/engine/webrtc.engine.ts#213-234) rather than `replaceTrack()`, ensuring proper SDP renegotiation with the new video m-line. The state machine prevents concurrent upgrades.

### 6. Browser event safety
`beforeunload` listener calls [endCall()](file:///d:/projects/social/frontend/src/features/call/signaling/signaling.adapter.ts#114-117) if a call is active. `online`/`offline` events trigger reconnection. `visibilitychange` can be used to pause quality monitoring when backgrounded.
